04384nmm a2200589Ia 9781479857364DE-B159720240328111612.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240328t20202020nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814798573647 a10.18574/nyu/9781479857364.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)680993  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLAW0360002bisacsh1 aWoody, William Douglas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUnderstanding Police Interrogation :bConfessions and Consequences /cWilliam Douglas Woody, Krista D. Forrest. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPsychoanalytic Crossroads ;v400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tIntroduction -- t1 Historical Developments in Policing and the Practice of Interrogation: The Emergence of Civilian Policing -- t2 The Current Nature of Police Interrogation -- t3 Deceptive Interrogation Tactics -- t4 False Confessions and Their Causes -- t5 Costs and Consequences of Deception, Coercion, and False Confessions: The Norfolk Four -- t6 Expert Testimony -- t7 Safeguards -- tConclusions and Recommendations -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAbout the Authors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aUses techniques from psychological science and legal theory to explore police interrogation in the United States Understanding Police Interrogation provides a single comprehensive source for understanding issues relating to police interrogation and confession. It sheds light on the range of factors that may influence the outcome of the interrogation of a suspect, which ones make it more likely that a person will confess, and which may also inadvertently lead to false confessions. There is a significant psychological component to police interrogations, as interrogators may try to build rapport with the suspect, or trick them into thinking there is evidence against them that does not exist. Also important is the extent to which the interrogator is convinced of the suspect’s guilt, a factor that has clear ramifications for today’s debates over treatment of black suspects and other people of color in the criminal justice system. The volume employs a totality of the circumstances approach, arguing that a number of integrated factors, such as the characteristics of the suspect, the characteristics of the interrogators, interrogation techniques and location, community perceptions of law enforcement, and expectations for jurors and judges, all contribute to the nature of interrogations and the outcomes and perceptions of the criminal justice system. The authors argue that by drawing on this approach we can better explain the likelihood of interrogation outcomes, including true and false confessions, and provide both scholars and practitioners with a greater understanding of best practices going forward.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 7aLAW / Ethics & Professional Responsibility.2bisacsh1 aForrest, Krista D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aGreene, Edie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479857364.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479857364423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479857364/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles